<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indian Group Sends UN Letter Seeking Mediation in Mexico </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2701012594 Paris AFP in Spanish 2235 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2701012594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 26 Jan (AFP) -- The Confederation of Indian 
Nationalities of Ecuador (Conaie) today asked for UN mediation 
to put an end to "the abuses committed against the brother 
peoples of Mexico." 
  In a letter sent to UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali, 
Conaie, which comprises the Indian communities of Ecuador, 
indicated that the uprising in Chiapas "is not an isolated 
incident but, rather, a social response to the prevailing 
conditions of poverty" extant in Latin America. Conaie said it 
is calling on the high-ranking international official to "in 
human terms" intervene in Mexico to help put an end to the 
abuses committed by against Indians in Ecuador. 
  The communique adds that it is the UN's "moral and political 
obligation" to guarantee the lives of the Indians in some way, 
because they are the "victims of the ferocious genocidal war 
waged by the Mexican Army." 
  It adds: "It cannot be possible that instead of providing 
human solutions to centuries of suffering, entire communities 
are being bombed." 
  The communique also says: "Measures such as declaring an 
amnesty or calling for a dialogue are insignificant in the 
solution of this dramatic situation if the economic interests of 
the dominant classes are not set aside." 
  According to Conaie, the events in Chiapas "are not promoted 
by a guerrilla group," but are "social reactions that should 
make all governments on the continent reflect about the need to 
review and change their neoliberal models." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

