<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havana Notes `Over-Confident' Clinton Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601173494 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1521 GMT 
26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2601173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. President Bill Clinton has just identified the 
top goals of his administration and Congress for 1994: To reform 
the health care system and reclaim the streets from crime and 
drugs. In his first State of the Union address given on 25 
January before a joint session of Congress and televised 
nationwide, the President emphasized domestic issues. However, 
he stressed that the change in the former socialist bloc into a 
market economy is a guarantee for Washington. Clinton urged 
Congress to approve this year his health reform bill, 
threatening to veto any legislation that does not guarantee 
private health insurance for every American that can never be 
taken away. 
  Clinton praised the participation of U.S. troops in missions 
such as Somalia, although he made no reference to the military 
failure endured in that country. 
  President Clinton's address to the Congress made use of an 
over-confident language which with he praised his program to 
reduce the budget deficit and the approval of NAFTA. In 
reference to the nationwide problem of crime, he solidly 
supported legislation to put another 100,000 policemen in the 
streets, permanently jail criminals after their third felony, 
and ban assault weapons. Clinton also turned down reducing the 
U.S. military budget despite the fact that many people had asked 
him to reduce it in order to pay for other government programs. 
In his address Clinton did not give figures for military 
expenses next year, although he stressed that the current budget 
guarantees the capabilities of the Armed Forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

