<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Teja, Ross Attend Workers Assembly at Havana Hospital </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601134394 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1200 
GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2601134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Public Health Minister Julio Teja has reaffirmed in 
Havana that implementing a system of cost controls by illnesses 
and areas should be the goal of all hospitals in Cuba in 
addition to efforts to improve the quality of services. Pedro 
Ross, member of the Politburo and secretary general of the Cuban 
Workers Federation, also attended the workers' assembly at 
Enrique Cabrera Teaching Hospital where doctors, specialists, 
nurses, and paramedics analyzed significant problems of the 
sector and national economy. 
  Teja described the hospital as a national vanguard in the 
implementation of the cost control system by pathologies and 
areas which permits, for example, knowing how much it costs to 
treat a myocardial case or for surgery for specific illnesses. 
During the meeting, several hospital workers stressed the need 
to know and discuss the material costs incurred by the hospital 
and a medical sciences teacher asked the cost of training 
medical personnel, stressing that as long as this is not known 
our economic awareness will be lacking. 
  In the closing of the first health workers assembly in 
Havana, Pedro Ross stressed that this process of consultation 
with the people seeks to find intelligent and effective 
measures, not only in financial terms, but also organizational 
in order to increase economic efficiency above all. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

