<H3> <TI>   Aristide, Canadian Foreign Minister Reach Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601233394 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2601233394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] President Aristide continues his tour of Canada. 
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide was due to meet with Canadian 
Prime Minister Jean Chretien on 25 January. 
  Following an initial meeting with Canadian Minister of 
Foreign Affairs Andre Ouellet, Jean-Bertrand Aristide, on 25 
January, also met with a Canadian delegation led by Mr. Ouellet. 
The two delegations, Haitian and Canadian, discussed a number of 
subjects, agreeing on the following points: 
  The imposition of a total embargo to relieve the situation 
in 
Haiti as soon as possible. 
  The training of a police force, outside of Haiti, with the 
collaboration of the United Nations or with the participation of 
several friendly countries. According to the agreement concluded 
by the two governments, this force will be trained not only in 
maintaining order and security, but also in respect for the laws 
and Constitution. [passage omitted] 
  During the talks, the two delegations also reviewed several 
areas of activity in which Haitian-Canadian cooperation would be 
broadened, including education, literacy, cooperatives, 
communication, and energy, following the return of democracy to 
Haiti. 
  It should also be noted that the possibility of a radio 
station broadcasting to Haiti has also been discussed. 

</TEXT>

