<H3> <TI>   Opposition Protests New Session of Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601174694 Bridgetown CANA in English 1555 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Basseterre, St. Kitts, 26 Jan, CANA -- A new session 
of the St. Kitts and Nevis Parliament opened Wednesday to noisy 
opposition protests. 
  Several supporters of the opposition St. Kitts-Nevis Labour 
Party demonstrated outside parliament as Governor General Sir 
Clement Arrindell read the traditional throne speech. 
  The Labour Party is pressing for fresh general elections, 
saying the minority coalition People's Action Movement/Nevis 
Reformation Party government had no moral authority to run the 
twin-island state. 
  The last general election here, in November 1993, produced 
no 
clear winner. PAM and the Labour Party each took four of the 11 
seats at stake. 
  The Nevis Reformation Party picked up just one seat and the 
Concerned Citizen's Movement two. 
  The coalition controls just five of the 11 parliamentary 
seats. 
  Prime Minister Kennedy Simmonds this week appealed for the 
maintenance of law and order ahead of the demonstration. 
  He said the police had given no permission for the 
demonstration and warned: "Those who break the law will be dealt 
with appropriately." 
  On Wednesday, there was a strong police presence outside the 
parliament building. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

