<H3> <TI>   Governor-General Opens Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601192994 Bridgetown CANA in English 1856 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Basseterre, St. Kitts, 26 Jan, CANA -- St 
Kitts-Nevis' ruling minority coalition which is under increasing 
pressure from the opposition to resign, on Wednesday outlined 
its agenda for the new five year term. 
  Governor-general Sir Clement Arrindell, delivering the 
traditional throne speech at the opening of a new session of 
parliament, said particular attention would be paid to the 
special needs of low wage earners, the unemployed, senior 
citizens, women and young people. 
  "We will strengthen mechanisms aimed at ensuring that the 
fruits of economic expansion are equitably shared and enjoyed by 
all categories of persons in the society," Sir Clement told the 
National Assembly. 
  "We will also continue to implement a variety of programmes 
.... To provide a social safety net for the protection of lower 
income groups," the head of state added. 
  As Sir Clement spoke, loud explosions could be heard outside 
as the police fired stun grenades to keep back a crowd of 
opposition supporters calling for new elections. 
  The four elected St Kitts-Nevis Labour Party MPs boycotted 
the ceremony. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

