<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reporting on Transportation Strike </TI></H3>
<H4>   Drivers Demand Release of 225 Strikers </H4>
<F P=102> PA2701015994 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0025 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2701015994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Managua, 26 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Dozens of taxi 
drivers have parked their vehicles in front of the Government 
Ministry building in this capital to demand the release of 225 
strikers who were arrested during the third day of an indefinite 
transportation strike. 
  The official radio station reported that the number of taxis 
participating in the protest could reach 200 vehicles and that 
police have intervened to guarantee the free movement of 
vehicles and pedestrians in the area. 
  Meanwhile, Sandinist Deputy William Ramirez told the media 
that police have stopped transferring 65 of the 225 arrested 
strikers to the Police Processing Unit out of fear of strikers 
staging a "rescue attempt." Police have charged the strikers 
with meeting with criminal intent and disrupting public order. 
The strikers were arrested after they set up the first 
barricades and "blockaded" streets with buses and taxis. 
  After reports by relatives of police beatings, Nicaraguan 
Government Minister Alfredo Mendieta authorized representatives 
of Human Rights Commissions to visit the prisoners to verify 
their situation. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

