<H3> <TI>   Endara, Gaviria Discuss Bilateral Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2701233594 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2701233594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ciro Ortega; from the "RPC Television News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] The focus of conversations held this afternoon 
between the Colombian and Panamanian presidents was bilateral 
ties. 
  Today, Colombian President Cesar Gaviria made a technical 
stopover at the National Air Service terminal in Tocumen, during 
which he met with his Panamanian counterpart Guillermo Endara. 
Cesar Gaviria declared his meeting with Endara at the airport 
had nothing to do with his possible participation in the bid for 
the post of OAS secretary general, nor was it intended to 
pressure the Endara government to support him. 
  [Begin Gaviria recording] We are working on all fronts. We 
want to have better control of our borders, but we are also 
working on commercial aspects. The Grancolombiana Merchant Fleet 
is working on an interesting project to begin ferry 
transportation on a daily basis between Cartagena, Colon, and 
Panama City. This is a very interesting project that for the 
time being will resolve the Darien gap problem and will allow us 
to have permanent transit not only between Panama and Colombia, 
but also between Central and South America. [end recording] 
  Gaviria stressed he came to strengthen bilateral ties. He 
then left the National Air Service terminal in Tocumen to attend 
the inauguration of new Honduran President Carlos Roberto Reina. 
  Meanwhile, Panamanian President Guillermo Endara called his 
brief meeting with Gaviria as positive. He also explained that 
his decision to not attend the inauguration of the new president 
of Honduras was because he prefers to stay in the country to 
think about possible changes he will make in his government 
cabinet. 

</TEXT>

