<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Causes Blackout in Guatemala City </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801043194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0346 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2801043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 28 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Part of 
downtown Guatemala City was blacked out at about 2130 on 27 
January following an explosion of unknown origin, which was 
heard by the population. It is not known whether there were any 
casualties. 
  The blackout affected areas near the Presidency of the 
Republic, the National Congress, the Archdiocese Palace, the 
Army Information Office, the headquarters of unions and popular 
organizations, the shopping center, and several foreign press 
agencies. 
  Guatemalan firemen told ACAN-EFE they are investigating the 
cause of the blackout and the reason behind the explosion. There 
is little traffic on the streets. 
  Guatemala has lived through a wave of terrorist attacks in 
the past few weeks, which the Army blames on the guerrillas who 
are trying to discourage the population from participating in 
the referendum next Sunday to approve or reject constitutional 
reforms that would move back elections for deputies and change 
the Supreme Court. The attacks have resulted in the death of one 
person. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-51990 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat019_g_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-019 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaves Capital, 2 Departments Powerless </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801045094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0416 GMT 28 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2801045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 27 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- A powerful 
dynamite charge exploded at an electric power pylon at 2125 
tonight, which left Guatemala City as well as the departments of 
Chimaltenango and Escuintla without power. The National Police 
report the explosion inflicted damage at the Guatemala-Norte 
station, east of Guatemala City, which distributes electricity 
from the Chixoy hydroelectric plant. 
  The terrorist act caused traffic jams in various parts of 
the 
city with traffic lights going out. Meanwhile, authorities from 
the National Electric Institute are working to restore power. 
The incident occurred 72 hours prior to the vote on a referendum 
to approve or reject 37 constitutional reforms. 
  In addition, military sources reported that Guatemalan Army 
troops sustained five casualties when they clashed with a column 
of the Revolutionary Organization of the Peoples in Arms (ORPA) 
at La Igualdad farm in La Reforma. 
  Soldier Julio Lopez Chavez told NOTIMEX that at 1300 the 1st 
and 3d Companies of the San Marcos Detachment searched La 
Igualdad farm, 280 km to the west of Guatemala City, where the 
guerrillas mined the field. The two Army companies detected the 
presence of the 15 ORPA rebels, who retreated to a very deep and 
rocky area when they noticed they had been discovered. 
  The soldiers proceeded to comb the area in search of the 
rebels. Two soldiers, Mauricio Hernandez Chun and Jose Pacual 
Merlo, died when they activated a claymore mine. Three soldiers 
were also injured by shrapnel from the mines. The soldiers' 
bodies and the injured soldiers were transferred to Coatepeque 
on the San Marcos Department border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

