<F P=100> Bahamas </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tribunal, Closure of Congress Demanded </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801012194 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2346 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2801012194 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 27 Jan (EFE) -- Approximately 1,000 
people participated in a demonstration today in front of the 
Haitian parliament demanding its dissolution and that a tribunal 
assume power. 
  The demonstrators expressed their support for the 
resolutions 
issued by the so-called "Congress of the Northern Citizens' 
Group" [Congres del Colectivo de Ciudadanos del Norte] 
recommending a military tribunal assume power. 
  In its 26 January session, the Chamber of Deputies did not 
discuss the resolution proposed by the northern citizens group. 
They thought it was "irrelevant" and instead announced the 
Chamber is working on a proposal asking President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide, currently in exile in Washington, to appoint a prime 
minister. Aristide was overthrown on 30 September 1991 by a 
group of military officers headed by General Raoul Cedras. 
  Following a traditional practice begun in the days of 
Francois Duvalier's dictatorship, the demonstrators were 
transported in vehicles from distant parts of the country to the 
capital. This time, the groups traveled in state-owned buses. 
  Commenting on the demonstration, Chamber of Deputies 
President Frantz Robert Monde said the fact that Haitians cannot 
reach an agreement to end the crisis "is sad." Monde added, "we 
will never yield under pressure." 
  Meanwhile, deputies have asked the leaders of the 
demonstration to assume their responsibility to prevent threats 
against the parliament. The demonstrators demanded parliament be 
closed because, according to them, "it is not complying with its 
mission." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

