<F P=100> Bahamas </F>
<F P=101> St. Kitts and Nevis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Wants `Outside Help' To Solve Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2701133694 Bridgetown CANA in English 2231 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2701133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Basseterre, St. Kitts, 26 Jan, CANA -- In the 
aftermath of clashes outside parliament, the opposition St. 
Kitts-Nevis Labour Party on Wednesday asked for outside help to 
solve political problems triggered by an inconclusive general 
election last November. 
  "It is time for the regional and international communities 
to 
come to the assistance of the people of St. Kitts and Nevis in 
finding a solution to our problems before the situation 
escalates further," the party said in a statement. 
  The party is pressing for fresh general elections, arguing 
that the minority coalition government formed by Prime Minister 
Kennedy Simmonds' People's Action Movement [PAM] and the Nevis 
Reformation Party has no moral authority to run the twin-island 
state. 
  The coalition holds five of the eleven seats in parliament. 
The Labour Party has four (like PAM) and the Concerned 
Citizen's Movement two. 
  On Wednesday, Labour Party supporters took their campaign 
for 
fresh elections to parliament, meeting for the first time since 
the November 29 election. 
  Outside parliament, they clashed with police, who fired stun 
grenades to keep back the crowd and clear the way after the 
presentation of the traditional throne speech for the exit of 
Governor-general Sir Clement Arrindell, Prime Minister Simmonds 
and other officials. 
  At least two persons were reported to have been injured. 
  The Labour Party said parliament "was opened amid loud 
noises 
from unarmed people calling for fresh elections, shattering 
glass and bottles, smoke bombs, tear gas explosions and 
concussion bombs fired on the protesters by the police". 
  The party said businesses and banks had been closed, school 
children sent home and government departments closed to the 
public. 
  It accused the government of "repressive and military action 
... just to open parliament". 
  The party said it was clear "that the people of St. Kitts do 
not intend to accept the Simmonds regime, and they would 
continue to struggle for the government of their choice and for 
fairness and justice until Dr Simmonds honours the agreement he 
made with the national church leaders for fresh elections within 
six months". 
  Simmonds described the protest action as "unfortunate and 
really distressing". 
  The police reported the incident had been brought under 
control by midday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52028 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat019_b_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-019 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Bahamas </F>
<F P=101> St. Vincent and the Grenadines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister on Talks With European Delegate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL2601184794 Bridgetown CANA in English 1730 GMT 26 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> FL2601184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kingstown, St. Vincent, 25 Jan, CANA -- St Vincent 
and the Grenadines prime minister, James Mitchell, says 
government intends to become more involved in negotiations with 
the British fruit-buying company, Geest on contracts for the 
sale of bananas in Europe. 
  "We are preparing our negotiations with Geest and the 
government intends to get more active in the negotiations with 
Geest in the future," he said. 
  "We can't leave it entirely up to the (Banana Growers) 
Association because they do not have the expertise to deal with 
this critical issue." 
  Mitchell was providing an update on the government's 
position 
on bananas and the outcome of recent discussions with Phillipe 
Darmuzey, the European delegate to the Caribbean. 
  He said action was to be taken on three fronts as far as the 
european union was concerned. 
  Efforts are to be made to access Stabex [expansion not 
given] 
funds provided under the Lome Convention as compensation for 
loss of earnings on exports of bananas. 
  The possibility of accessing funds under the Lome VI 
regional 
indicative programme for agricultural assistance and bananas 
particularly was also addressed, Mitchell said. 
  Funds under this programme were recently dislodged following 
discussions with European officials in Brussels, he said. 
  "Now that the Greek presidency is taking certain initiatives 
in the European Union we discussed how we could assist the 
process in lobbying or by any other activity in ensuring we have 
a special assistance fund developed for assistance of the banana 
industry," Mitchell reported. 
  On the question of a reported proposal by the U.S. company 
Chiquita to purchase bananas from the Windward Islands, Mitchell 
said no proposal had been put forward. 
  "We are prepared to look at all the options but I would not 
want to interfere with the long-standing understanding 
relationship with geest unless I were to see something 
substantial," Mitchell said. 
  A one-year interim contract with geest expired at the end of 
1993 and the Governments of Grenada, Dominica, St Lucia and St 
Vincent and the Grenadines and banana officials are preparing to 
re-negotiate. 
  Officials of the Windward Islands Banana Association 
(Winban) 
have prepared a document for perusal by governments and industry 
officials going into the negotiations. 
  Sources said the removal of a clause which binds the 
Windward 
Islands to selling bananas exclusively to Geest is among the 
proposals which Winban has made. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

