<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Franco Promotes South American Free Trade Zone </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2601015794 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
25 Jan 94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2601015794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- President Itamar Franco took advantage 
of his meeting with Colombian President Cesar Gaviria Trujillo 
last week to insist on the need for establishing the South 
American Free Trade Zone, a proposal he made last year before 
the Rio Group meeting held in Chile, and which strives to group 
together the ten member countries of ALADI (Latin American 
Integration Association). In assessing his trip to Leticia, a 
Colombian town near the Brazilian border, President Franco told 
JORNAL DO BRASIL that "Colombia is an important partner." 
Moreover, Foreign Minister Celso Amorim, who accompanied Franco 
in his trip to Leticia, said: "Through a free-trade zone we 
would be able to negotiate under better terms with other trade 
groups, such as NAFTA." 
  Franco and Gaviria installed the Brazilian-Colombian 
Neighborhood Commission, which will be entrusted with finding 
solutions to problems concerning the fight against narcotics, 
environmental protection, and the adoption of measures to 
improve health and education conditions and assist Amazonian 
indigenous groups. 
  The ideas is to expedite negotiations with Colombia before 
Gaviria leaves the presidency. Colombia is holding presidential 
elections at the end of the first half of this year, and Gaviria 
will be running for the OAS General Secretariat. The proposal 
to establish a South American Free Trade Zone (comprised of the 
Mercosur [Common Market of the South] countries Brazil, 
Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay; Chile; and the five Andean 
Group member countries Colombia, Peru, Ecuador and Bolivia) was 
also discussed at the Mercosur presidential summit held in 
Colonia, Uruguay last week. 

</TEXT>

