<H3> <TI>   PFL Gains Government Support on Constitutional Reform Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY2501152694 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
24 Jan 94 p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2501152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The government will cease to be a mere observer 
of the constitutional reform issue and take the initiative, 
seeking to initiate reforms. The PFL [Liberal Front Party] has 
managed to convince Finance Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso 
that revisions are in the best interest of the government. 
After lunching with Fernando Henrique last week, Marco Maciel 
(PE) [Pernambuco State] -- the PFL bloc leader in the Senate -- 
and Deputy Luis Eduardo Magalhaes (BA) [Bahia State] -- the PFL 
bloc leader in the Chamber of Deputies -- believe the government 
is the newest ally of the revisionists who are struggling for 
votes now. 
  Maciel told JORNAL DO BRASIL yesterday afternoon: "We now 
have a very important partner, namely the government." During 
their lunch, the PFL leaders explained the importance of the 
revision for the government's economic program. Neither the 
fiscal adjustment nor the 1994 budget will be approved without 
constitutional changes that necessarily involve a reform. The 
senator claimed: "It is essential to begin the revision this 
week." He guaranteed: "The minister totally agrees with this 
point of view." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

