<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Report Duran-Ballen Cancels Trip to Peru </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1901002194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2051 GMT 18 Jan 
94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1901002194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 18 Jan (PL) -- President Sixto Duran-Ballen 
today canceled his visit to Peru scheduled later this week 
because of diplomatic difficulties that have arisen in recent 
days between the two countries. 
  Sources close to the president told PRENSA LATINA that the 
president decided a few hours ago to cancel his trip to Lima, 
Peru, and that -- for the time being -- no date has been set for 
his meeting with Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori. 
  Ecuadoran Foreign Minister Diego Paredes recently said that 
Duran-Ballen's trip to Lima was subject to some diplomatic 
details that were being worked out, inasmuch as this was a very 
complex trip because the topics to be discussed were very 
delicate. 
  One week ago, Fujimori told Ecuadoran newsmen that he was 
waiting for Duran-Ballen with open arms, but only to discuss 
topics on integration and economic cooperation and that he would 
not talk about the so-called "border conflict." 
  Diplomatic sources feel the Peruvian president's remarks and 
negative reaction from various public sectors prompted the 
Ecuadoran president to cancel his trip. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

