<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Argentina Agree To Sign Extradition Treaty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901021194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0112 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901021194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 28 Jan (YONHAP) -- South Korean Vice 
Chairman of the National Assembly Ho Kyong-man met Argentine 
Justice Minister Jorge Maiorano Friday and agreed that the two 
countries sign an extradition treaty within this year at the 
earliest. 
  The two agreed that Seoul and Buenos Aires exchange a 
memorandum of understanding on the matter and expand exchanges 
of law-enforcement officials to strengthen bilateral judicial 
cooperation. 
  "Judicial cooperation is very much in need considering more 
than 35,000 Koreans are living in Argentina and bilateral 
exchanges are growing," Ho pointed out. 
  On this understanding, the two countries decided to sign an 
extradition treaty as soon as possible after consultation with 
the Korean Justice Ministry, he said. 
  On Saturday, Ho finishes his agenda in Argentina and leads 
the four-man National Assembly delegation to Chile, where he is 
scheduled to meet President-designate Eduardo Frei and discuss 
problems of mutual concern. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

