<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel's Mosad Said Behind Libyan's Abduction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC0101103794 Cairo AL-SHA'B in Arabic 24 Dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC0101103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-SHA'B </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mahmud Bakri] </F>
  [Text] Well-informed sources have told AL-SHA'B that the 
Israeli intelligence service (Mosad) is probably behind the 
abduction of Libyan oppositionist Mansur al-Kikhya. The sources 
say that it is part of a scheme to undermine Egyptian-Libyan 
relations by blaming the operation on Libya and paving the way 
for a military strike against the Libyan Jamahiriyah. 
  The circles noted that an eight-member team from the U.S. 
intelligence service (CIA) will arrive in Cairo within a few 
days to investigate the disappearance of al-Kikhya. This is 
part of the U.S. Administration's plan to highlight the issue to 
adopt a military plan to strike at Colonel Mu'ammar 
al-Qadhdhafi's regime under the pretext of his violations of 
human rights. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton had instructed the U.S. 
intelligence service to adopt a speedy plan to identify the 
location of al-Kikhya and investigate claims that Libyan 
elements kidnapped him in collaboration with Egyptian security 
elements. He asked President Mubarak to intervene to clear up 
the mystery of al-Kikhya's disappearance. The visit to Libya of 
Dr. Usamah al-Baz, first Foreign Ministry under secretary and 
director of the President's Office for Political Affairs, came 
within this context. 
  In the past few days Cairo has received several U.S. reports 
accusing Libya of being involved in al-Kikhya's disappearance. 
The U.S. reports accused Libyan diplomats in Cairo of planning 
the operation and called on the Egyptian Government to downgrade 
its relations with Libya as a quick reaction to the operation. 
However, Egypt told Washington that it would not adopt any 
measures against Libya before the accusation is confirmed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

