<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   People's Assembly Passes Unified Tax Bill </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC3112085493 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> NC3112085493 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a session that lasted until the early hours 
of this morning, the People's Assembly passed the Unified Tax 
Bill in its final reading. Prime Minister Dr. 'Atif Sidqi said 
the law, as issued, is well-balanced considering the amendments 
that have been made to it. He explained that the government was 
responsive to all the views offered by the deputies. He added 
that a high-level committee chaired by the justice minister will 
amend all relevant legislation to bring it into line with 
current circumstances. 
  People's Assembly Speaker Dr. Ahmad Fathi Surur asserted 
that 
the new law, which was discussed at length, contains no 
contradictions of Islamic shari'ah. 
  After passing the new bill, the People's Assembly adjourned 
until 8 January 1994. The Assembly approved articles 85, 87, 
and 88 pertaining to tax exemptions for families. It also 
approved Article 90, which specifies the tax rates as follows: 
  Section 1: 20 percent on income of up to 2,000 pounds. 
  Section 2: 27 percent on income greater than 2,500 pounds 
and up to 7,000 pounds. 
  Section 3: 35 percent on income greater than 7,000 pounds 
and up to 16,000 pounds. 
  Section 4: 40 percent on income greater than 16,000 
pounds and up to 27,000 pounds. 
  Section 5: 45 percent on income greater than 27,000 
pounds and up to 68,000 pounds. 
  Section 6: 48 percent on income greater than 68,000 
pounds. 
  Regarding income from salaries and similar and other revenue 
[as heard], the tax rate on them will be the same as that in 
section 1 -- 20 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-52128 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes001_d_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-001 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Qadhdhafi Warns of Return of Colonialism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201222094 Tripoli Libyan Television Network in Arabic 
1923 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0201222094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Libyan Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Address by leader of the revolution Colonel Mu'ammar </F>
al-Qadhdhafi in Surman and Bu 'Isa on 2 January -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] Brothers and sons of Surman, the world hears the 
strong voice of defiance from you. The voice of defiance is not 
only the voice of Mu'ammar al-Qadhdhafi, but it is the voice of 
the masses, the free masses. Here in Surman, the same as 
yesterday and the other days in other regions, everywhere there 
are people ready for confrontation; people who insist on living 
on the land of their fathers and ancestors freely, 
independently, and with pride. [passage omitted] 
  Let the world hear the voice of the masses of Bu 'Isa and 
Surman. Let the world hear the voice of the free masses, however 
much those around us surrender and whatever the shivers of the 
rulers of the Arab nation might be. They want the Arab nation 
to be subjugated to its enemies. Whatever those who surrender 
might do, whatever those who prostrate themselves might do, and 
whatever those who tremble might do, we have decided to live 
freely and with dignity on the land of our fathers and 
ancestors. [passage omitted] 
  For this reason, to live in freedom and live a life worthy 
of 
the free man, for this reason we have decided that we will 
confront anyone who wants to challenge us over the land of our 
fathers and forefathers. This is our land, the land of the 
fathers and forefathers. We paid for this land with the lives 
of our fathers and forefathers. We have written its history in 
their dear blood. We will not squander one grain of sand of this 
land. The banners of this land will never fly under the banners 
of the colonialists. No foreigner or colonialist can settle 
this land. We challenge anyone who wants to challenge us. 
[passage omitted] 
  The defiance started in Libya; the cry of confrontation 
started in Libya; and the preparations for battle started in 
Libya. 
  Brothers, we hear now another voice from Sudan. Sudan 
announced yesterday the expulsion of the British ambassador 
because he considered Sudan a British colony. 
  The dreams of the colonialists have returned again. The 
dreams of the West have returned again. Their ambitions in 
Tunisia, Algeria, Sudan, Libya, and everywhere in the Arab world 
have returned. Their ambitions have returned again. 
  Yesterday Britain acted as if Sudan was not celebrating the 
38th anniversary of its independence. Britain ignored Sudan as 
an independent state. Britain ignored Sudan's dignity and 
Sudan's independence. Britain proceeded along the course of 
marching on the Arab homeland, trampling on the dignity of the 
Arab homeland, and Arab existence with an indifference to the 
national sovereignty of the peoples of the Arab nation. 
  Its ambassador quite insolently interfered in Khartoum's 
domestic affairs. Brothers, look at this. It is not the year 
1881 or 1882 or 1830, and it is not even 1911 [the date of the 
Italian invasion of Libya]. Today it is 1993-94. Britain 
behaved as if Sudan was a colony that belonged to King Faruq and 
Faruq belonged to Britain. This is how Britain sees Egypt's and 
Sudan's independence. 
  Yesterday, however, the Sudanese people headed by al-Bashir 
announced that the confrontation was not only in Libya, it has 
extended to Sudan by the expulsion of the British ambassador. 
Sudan said to him that Sudan is an independent state and only 
death can separate it. 
  This is what happened yesterday. The colonialists recognized 
the legitimacy of the Somali national resistance. They 
recognized Aidid as its national leader and that they must 
negotiate with him after they used to say that he was a war 
criminal who must be captured. 
  Brothers, this is a retreat in the face of the determination 
of the Somali people to uphold truth and defeat lies. The truth 
is that every nation has the right to live on the land of its 
fathers and forefathers in freedom and dignity. Brothers, all 
the peoples possess the right to die in defense of their honor 
and independence. 
  The colonialists will pull back when they face these [words 
indistinct] these challenges and this determination; the 
determination of peoples to live freely brothers. Yes, they 
will have to be very wary. This is coming from the masses of 
Surman and Bu 'Isa only, not to mention the masses of the Arab 
nation and the masses of Libya as a whole. There are masses in 
Tunisia, Algeria, Egypt, Sudan, Lebanon, Syria, Palestine, Iraq, 
the Arabian Peninsula, Yemen, and Sudan [repeated as heard]. 
There are innumerable masses and the colonialists will find it 
difficult to impose their dominion again on a nation that is 
beating the drums of confrontation, a nation that has decided to 
live freely. 
  Yes, brothers, we are not just talking, we are demonstrating 
with deeds. The national resistance in southern Lebanon is 
daily writing in blood the words that we are speaking now, and 
it is paving the path of liberation with the bodies of the 
martyrs of Hizballah and the Lebanese national resistance. 
There is fighting every day [word indistinct] in southern 
Lebanon and Palestine under the leadership of Palestinian Jihad, 
the Fatah Eagles, Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement], the 
Popular Front, the Popular Democratic Front, the Popular 
Front-General Command, the Fatah of Intifadah, and 
Fatah-Revolutionary Council. [passage omitted] 
  Brothers, those who sell Palestine now in a public auction 
will be punished by the Palestinian people. Brothers, those who 
betray the Arab nation will see their just fate. 
  Brothers, we did not decide to go outside our borders. We 
did not decide to commit aggression. We did not decide to 
sabotage the world. We did not decide to trample on 
international legitimacy. We only decided to live with respect 
and dignity on our land. This is what we demanded and we will 
defend it until death. They are the ones who trampled on the 
international treaties and tore the UN Charter. They are the 
ones who violated international law. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

