<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Jordanian Mediation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN3112123793 Amman AKHIR KHABAR in Arabic 30-31 Dec 93 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN3112123793 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHIR KHABAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Informed political sources have revealed the secrets 
of the recent visit to Yemen by [Jordanian Royal Court Chief] 
al-Sharif Zayd Bin-Shakir. The visit, according to these 
sources, was more than just a mediation mission to resolve the 
Yemeni crisis which has reached a difficult stage. 
  The sources, who met Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih 
last week, told AKHIR KHABAR that the Yemeni leadership asked 
al-Sharif Zayd to help it reorganize the Yemeni Armed Forces 
which appear to be gradually affected by the ongoing tribal and 
party conflict in Yemen. 
  Al-Sharif Zayd will supervise the drafting of a plan to 
reorganize the Yemeni Armed Forces which are facing technical 
problems in terms of organization, training, general 
mobilization, and combat capabilities. 
  Our sources added that al-Sharif Zayd was accompanied by a 
number of specialists who reviewed the plan with the Yemeni 
leadership. The sources added that the Yemeni president 
officially asked the Jordanian leadership to prepare such a 
plan. The Jordanian leadership held contacts with all parties 
to find common grounds that would defuse the crisis before it 
explodes. 
  Last week, the two parties to the Yemeni dispute agreed to 
neutralize the Armed Forces and to avoid the provocations that 
would involve them in the conflict. 
  Yemeni diplomatic sources in Amman told AKHIR KHABAR that 
the 
Yemeni leadership explained to mediators that it wants to remove 
the roots of division which threaten the Yemeni Army ranks 
following the emergence of signs of division. The sources 
added: The Yemeni leadership is unanimous on the need to carry 
out a comprehensive national military orientation plan and to 
busy the Armed Forces with military training to keep them away 
from tension points that would affect them as a result of the 
tribal conflict. 
  The sources linked the recent Jordanian-Yemeni contacts with 
the new trends produced by military incidents and tension. The 
sources said: The Jordanian assistance in this regard will come 
within the framework of the vital and important role played by 
the Jordanian leadership which enjoys the confidence of all 
parties in the conflict. 

</TEXT>

