<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting Between Rabbani, Dostam Forces </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kabul Transmitter Down </H4>
<F P=102> LD0301111394 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1030 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0301111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kabul remains the scene of intense battles between 
the warring factions for a third day. Thousands of artillery 
shells, bullets, and rockets have hit various districts of 
Kabul, leaving hundreds dead. Here is our colleague with a 
telephone report from Kabul on the situation: 
  [Unidentified correspondent] I am reporting from Kabul. The 
battle between the warring factions intensified this morning. 
As a result of artillery fire, Kabul radio's transmitter is out 
of action. 
  Forces of Prime Minister Golboddin Hekmatyar's Hezb-e Eslami 
[Islamic Party of Afghanistan] have joined General Dostam's 
forces, and forces loyal to Hezb-e Ettehad-e Eslami [Islamic 
Union of Afghanistan] of Rasul Sayyaf have joined those of 
President Borhanoddin Rabbani, and have turned Kabul into a 
battle arena since dawn this morning. 
  Another report from Kabul's hospitals indicate that 650 
wounded people, mostly civilians, are hospitalized in two city 
hospitals. Reports from the southeastern district of Kabul, the 
main area of concentration of General Dostam's forces, indicate 
that the intensity of the clashes prevents the people from 
evacuating their dead and wounded from houses. Columns of thick 
smoke cover the sky above Kabul and in the city itself nothing 
but the fire of artillery exchanges is visible. 

</TEXT>

