<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government `Will Not Withdraw' Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA0201171094 Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network in 
Arabic 1500 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> EA0201171094 </F>
<F P=104>  Omdurman Republic of Sudan Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Muhammad al-Amin Khalifah, the speaker of the 
Transitional National Assembly, has told our radio correspondent 
that the Sudanese Government will not withdraw from the decision 
it has issued about the British ambassador's departure from the 
country within a period not exceeding two weeks. He added: We 
have asked for the British ambassador's departure in an attempt 
to improve relations between the two countries. It is for 
Britain to nominate another person from its embassy to be acting 
ambassador. He stressed that the matter was legitimate and does 
occur in diplomatic relations. He pointed out that the British 
Government's demand that the Sudanese Government should 
reconsider its decision is a matter which is not legitimate in 
these relations. 
  He also made reference to the visit of the Archbishop of 
Canterbury to Sudan. He said that he considered the archbishop 
as a VIP and he ought to have entered Sudan through the capital, 
Khartoum, but regrettably he went to see the rebels and visited 
the citizens who were under the control of the rebels. 

</TEXT>

