<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decision `Could be Reversed' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0301135394 Rabat MAP in English 1323 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0301135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rabat MAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] London, Jan 3 (MAP) -- Sudan has accused the British 
ambassador to Khartoum, Peter Streams, of working against its 
efforts to mend fences with the West. But a "highly-placed 
political sources" hinted in a report in the government 
newspaper "AL-INGAZ AL-WATANI" that the expulsion order could be 
reversed if Britain showed understanding of the reasons behind 
the order. On Thursday Sudan said that it was giving Streams 
two weeks to leave. Britain has given Sudan until Tuesday to 
reverse the decision or face retaliation. The Sudanese 
official said that the expulsion had nothing to do with the 
ambassador's contacts with Sudanese opposition leaders or 
controversy over a visit to southern Sudan by George Carey, the 
archbishop of Canterbury. 

</TEXT>

