<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denies Refugee Excursion Into Eritrea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA0301160594 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1025 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA0301160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 3 Jan (SUNA) -- Foreign Minister Husayn 
Sulayman Abu-Salih has said that Sudan has been playing host to 
refugees in accordance with the rules of asylum and they are not 
allowed to undertake any armed activity or any other political 
action against their own countries. 
  In a statement he made to the newspaper AL-INQADH AL-WATANI 
published today concerning the infiltration of some armed 
elements across the border [into Eritrea] under full security 
cover, he said that no reports had been received about what 
could be considered [words indistinct] and to disturb the peace 
in the refugee camps. His excellency added that all the refugee 
camps were under the full administrative control of the UNHCR. 
They are far away from the border and constitute no threat of 
any kind against neighboring countries. He stressed that the 
UNHCR's priority [words indistinct] monitors all activities by 
the refugees and does not allow any violation of the 
international conventions governing asylum. 
  It is worth mentioning that the number of Eritrean refugees 
in Sudan exceeds 500,000 living in 30 different places. 
Eritrean President Isayas Afewerki announced that his forces 
had killed more than 20 persons who tried to infiltrate into 
Eritrea from Sudan on 16 December. He described Sudan as the 
source of the problem. He accused the infiltrators as having 
come to liberate the area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

