<DATE1>  3 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rabin, Peres Reject Taba Talks for `Time Being' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0301165694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 3 Jan 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0301165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Foreign Minister 
Shim'on Peres today decided not to resume the Taba talks for the 
time being due to the PLO's positions. Nabil Sha'th phoned 
Shim'on Peres several times today, and the two are slated to 
hold another phone conversation in the next few hours. Our 
political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports: 
  Jerusalem sources are saying that conditions are not yet 
ripe 
for resuming the Taba talks. What does this mean? In a fax 
sent by Nabil Sha'th, the PLO demands that the Taba talks will 
revisit all the issues previously negotiated in Oslo, 
Versailles, and Cairo. Israel, on the other hand, maintains that 
the document formulated during the Liaison Committee's session 
in Cairo is a binding summation of all three meetings. Israel 
contends that in Cairo the delegations managed to overcome the 
controversies which were not solved in Oslo and Versailles. 
Officials in Jerusalem today learned that not only is 'Arafat 
unwilling to approve the document formulated by Peres and 
Abu-Mazin [Mahmud 'Abbas], but that the PLO wants to renegotiate 
the gaps which have apparently been bridged in Cairo. 
  Following their private meeting this morning, Yitzhaq Rabin 
and Shim'on Peres stated that Israel considers it impossible to 
resume the Taba talks for the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho 
First plan. 
  Despite the present stalemate, various sources -- some of 
them close to the PLO leadership -- assess that by next week 
conditions will ripen and that Foreign Minister Peres will find 
the right formulations to clear the way for resuming the Taba 
talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

