<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israel Sends Reply to Tunis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA0201184194 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0201184194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Political correspondent Gadi Sukenik report] </F>
  [Excerpts] Israel is not prepared to resume the political 
talks with the PLO under the conditions created by 'Arafat. A 
letter to this effect signed by Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres 
was faxed this evening to the PLO leaders. 
  The prime minister stated today: I have time, let the guys 
in Tunis start sweating a little now. In the meantime, cabinet 
ministers have begun floating new ideas. For example, in an 
internal session today, Minister Moshe Shahal said he believes 
we should halt the deliberations about an interim arrangement 
and proceed directly to discuss the permanent arrangement in the 
territories. Our political correspondent Gadi Sukenik reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Sukenik] [passage omitted] Israel today 
sent its reply to the heads of the Palestinian delegation in 
Cairo and Tunis by fax, as the Palestinians did. The principle 
stated in the Israeli message: Changes in the understandings may 
be discussed, but not ignored. In other words, 'Arafat should 
get off his high horse. [passage omitted] 
  Rabin and Peres today told cabinet ministers they decided to 
resume the economic talks with the PLO in Paris at once. They 
conveyed their impression that 'Arafat is not bothered by the 
situation in the territories. At the same time, they reiterated 
that the PLO's standing in the territories has been 
deteriorating and that the money promised to it has not been 
coming through. 
  The new situation is leading to new ideas. In an internal 
session today -- and only in such a forum at this point -- 
Minister Moshe Shahal said: We should drop the deliberations 
about the interim arrangement and proceed directly to a 
discussion about the permanent arrangement in the territories. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

