<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres on Talks With PLO, Syrian Involvement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0201095594 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
0805 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0201095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres by </F>
unidentified correspondent; Peres speaking in English fading 
into Hungarian translation; place and date not given--recorded] 
  [Text] [Correspondent] A definitive settlement of the 
Palestinian-Israeli conflict cannot be expected by tomorrow; but 
it can now be expected. Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, 
with whom I recorded a brief interview, is himself visibly 
confident. 
  [Begin recording] [Correspondent] Mr. Peres, do you think 
that Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] will be able to prevent 
the agreement? 
  [Peres] They might try to prevent the agreement coming into 
being but I do not think they will succeed. The majority of 
Palestinians, just as the majority of Israelis, too, want peace. 
Consequently, the decision is not in Hamas' hands. They murder 
people and they would like to annihilate the peace process 
itself by murdering people, but I do not think they will get far 
with this. 
  [Correspondent] How do you see the future of the 
Palestinian-Israeli agreement after the postponement of the 
first deadline for the Israeli military withdrawal? 
  [Peres] It was not a postponement. You know, the parties 
concerned agreed in Oslo that they would allow one month after 
the signing for informal meetings; they allowed another two 
months for the agreement to be translated, so that every tiny 
detail could be clarified. But it turned out that the time at 
our disposal was extremely short. We are unable to settle all 
necessary matters in two months. Now we have to clarify just 
how much time we still need. 
  [Correspondent] Finally, how do you see the possibility of 
Syria's involvement? 
  [Peres] Well, we would like the Syrians to be involved in 
the 
settlement efforts, since we would like to put a full-stop to 
the old conflicts in the region and we would like to build a new 
Middle East for the future. Naturally, we need new partners for 
this, partners with whom we can work together. At present, 
Syria is not showing too much flexibility [hajlekonysag]. But 
it is also a fact that at the time of the latest visit by U.S. 
State Secretary Warren Christopher, Syrian President Hafiz 
al-Asad indicated with certain gestures that Syria does not wish 
to be left out of the negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

